A new law in #Germany went into effect in late July 2021 allowing L4 fully automated cars to #drive regularly in designated areas in the future, they can be operated utilizing an #automated driving function, without the need of a human driver, under strict conditions.

In #Europe, we may see automated functions like #highway pilots for long distances by 2030. But for cars used privately, the technical regulations for approving L4 functionality do not exist yet in Europe but could be expected in 2024 at the earliest.

According to Audi‚Äôs Head of General Counsel Legal Services, Uta Klawitter, the 3 biggest challenges are the #technology itself, gaining social acceptance and harmonizing the regulations at an international, or at least the European level.

Concerning the legal framework, Germany is already ahead of the curve. #Audi and @cariad_tech, for instance, have already demonstrated that last year with the automated valet parking showcase at the #IAA in #Munich.

In the #US, people are more curious about technical #innovations and therefore, tolerate more risks. By contrast, German legislators are rightly open to this evolutionary technology in smaller steps to minimize the possible risks.

All of these facts and more can be found in a recent interview with Audi‚Äôs Head of General Counsel Legal Services Uta Klawitter, as she dives deeper into the topic of automated #mobility. Read more: https://t.co/ibgC8JiooO

manufacturing or recycling of our vehicles are, at least in terms of quantity, offset by voluntary compensation projects worldwide. CO2 emissions generated during the operational phase of a vehicle (i.e. as of the time the vehicle is handed over to the customer) ...
are not taken into account.
